{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-09T20:22:25Z", "url": "https://www.pcworld.com/article/2672946/amd-debuts-cheaper-ryzen-8000-hx-chips-for-gaming-laptops-as-tariffs-rage.html", "publishedAt": "2025-04-09T20:22:25Z", "content": "Skip to contentType your search and hit enter\r\nWhen you purchase through links in our articles, we may earn a small commission. This doesn't affect our editorial independence\r\n.\r\nNo one wants to spenâ€¦ [+2543 chars]", "title": "AMD debuts cheaper Ryzen 8000 HX chips for gaming laptops as tariffs rage", "fullContent": "No one wants to spend more than they have to right nowâ€¦meaning that it might have been an opportune time for AMD to debut its latest Ryzen 8000 Core HX mobile processors for gaming notebooks, which lack some of the features of the Ryzen 9000 series.\n\nEssentially, the new Ryzen 8000 HX series, known as Dragon Range Refresh, is quite similar to the â€œDragon Rangeâ€ Ryzen 7000 HX series that AMD launched in January 2023, and should sit below the Ryzen 9 9955HX and Ryzen 9 9850HX AMD launched in conjunction with the Ryzen 9955HX3D this past January. All three of those latter chips used AMDâ€™s Zen 5 architecture.\n\nAMDâ€™s Ryzen 8000HX lineup. AMD\n\nBoth AMDâ€™s Ryzen 7000 HX and the refreshed Ryzen 8000 HX parts both use the older Zen 4 architecture, however, and thereâ€™s no NPU, either. In fact, both the older Ryzen 7000 parts and the latest Ryzen 8000 HX series both feature processors with up to 16 cores and 32 threads and can be used in laptops with 45 to 75 watts of thermal design power, or TDP. (The default is 55W.) Both families use AMDâ€™s TSMCâ€™s 5nm process. One of the more significant changes AMD made has been to phase out the six-core Ryzen 5 7645HX for an 8-core Ryzen 7 8745HX.\n\nThe 8000HX Series is a refresh of the 7000HX Series with a few key differences in clock speeds and firmware, an AMD representative said in an email. â€œHowever, the 8000HX Series is intended to be paired with newer, more powerful discrete GPUs, and offers users more options for those looking to get into systems with the latest graphics,â€ he added.\n\nAMDâ€™s Ryzen 8000 HX series do include integrated graphics, though the Ryzen 610M inside the 8945HX and its two RDNA 2 graphics cores arenâ€™t enough to serve as a gaming GPU, of course. Laptop makers will want to add a discrete GPU for that.\n\nAMDâ€™s new Ryzen 8000 HX chips will use DDR5 SODIMM memory and have 28 lanes of PCI Express 5.0 available."}
{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-09T20:12:08Z", "url": "https://www.pcworld.com/article/2672572/try-microsofts-tech-tutor-copilot-vision-for-windows-right-now.html", "publishedAt": "2025-04-09T20:12:08Z", "content": "Skip to contentType your search and hit enter\r\nWhen you purchase through links in our articles, we may earn a small commission. This doesn't affect our editorial independence\r\n.\r\nMicrosoft has begun â€¦ [+3399 chars]", "title": "Try Microsoftâ€™s tech tutor, Copilot Vision for Windows, right now", "fullContent": "Microsoft has begun rolling out a test of Copilot Vision on PCs, a new feature that gives Windows the ability to â€œseeâ€ what youâ€™re looking at on your PC and suggest some next steps you can take.\n\nCopilot Vision debuted (sort of) last December as a Windows-centric version of Copilot Vision for Edge, which was quite underwhelming. But at the companyâ€™s 50th anniversary party, Microsoft showed off how a Windows-native Copilot Vision could walk you through complex apps like Adobe Photoshop, then visually show you what to do next.\n\nI thought the demo had enough potential to select it as the best Copilot demo Microsoft showed during the event.\n\nCopilot Vision isnâ€™t always on. Youâ€™ll need to first click the small â€œbinocularsâ€ icon within Copilot to launch Vision, then specifically enable Copilot Vision for the application you want help with.\n\nI have a number of questions about Copilot Vision for Windows. How deeply does it know what to do? What can it see? Can it understand what it sees well enough to be useful? Iâ€™d say a key test would be its ability to walk me through a task on an unfamiliar piece of softwareâ€”some on-screen handholding could be extremely helpful, if Vision got it right. But there will be those (me included!) who probably donâ€™t want any help with more private matters like, say, personal finances.\n\nA Microsoft example of Copilot Vision for Windows. Microsoft\n\nYou have a chance to try Copilot Vision out for yourself, as Microsoft has started rolling it out for wider testing. Microsoft says youâ€™ll need to be enrolled in one of its Windows Insider programs, but it doesnâ€™t matter which one. However, itâ€™s being rolled out via the Microsoft Store rather than through Windows Update. If you go to the Store app and download the latest Copilot update, you might get it. (Officially, youâ€™ll need version 1.25034.133.0 or higher.)\n\nâ€œThe above-mentioned features are gradually rolling out so not all Insiders will get the update right away,â€ Microsoft said in a blog post. Copilot Vision will debut on US PCs first. As of press time, it has yet to land on the first Insider PC I checked, a Copilot+ laptop.\n\nWhen you update Copilot to get Vision, youâ€™ll also get a new Copilot capability with it: desktop file search. Although you might be able to find a file via File Explorer, you should now also be able to query Copilot with questions like â€œWhere is my resume?â€ and Copilot should find it and link to it. Microsoft also encourages you to try more sophisticated searches, such as finding the trip-planning document you worked on last week. The new Copilot search supports most file types and can read .DOCX, .XLSX, .PPTX, .TXT, .PDF, and .JSON files\n\nThe more sophisticated search option mirrors what Microsoft is doing elsewhere within Windowsâ€”specifically semantic search, which is one of Microsoftâ€™s new Windows 11 features debuting this month."}
{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-09T17:59:54Z", "url": "https://www.pcworld.com/article/2662137/amazon-shein-temu-prices-could-skyrocket-as-tariff-loophole-ends.html", "publishedAt": "2025-04-09T17:59:54Z", "content": "Skip to contentType your search and hit enter\r\nWhen you purchase through links in our articles, we may earn a small commission. This doesn't affect our editorial independence\r\n.\r\nYou may not be awareâ€¦ [+3494 chars]", "title": "Amazon, Shein, Temu prices could skyrocket as tariff loophole ends", "fullContent": "You may not be aware of it, but purchases youâ€™ve made though overseas online shops like Shein or AliExpress or Temu have snuck through an online loophole that limited how much youâ€™ve paid. That loophole is now closed, thanks to the ongoing Trump tariffs â€” and it will likely get dramatically worse.\n\nA year ago, goods imported into the United States that were valued at less than $800 could be imported duty free, without being affected by tariffs. This was known as the de minimis exemption, and meant that individual consumers could largely escape any trade wars going on between nations, while still essentially being taxed for more expensive consumer goods and appliances.\n\nThat way of doing business ended April 2 on goods imported from China, according to an executive order from President Trump that closed the de minimis exemption and applied a tariff of 30 percent. Now, thatâ€™s changed yet again.\n\nAccording to an amendment to the order filed Tuesday night, the United States is now dramatically raising de minimis tariffs in line with Trumpâ€™s existing tariffs on China, which as of April 9 stood at 104 percent. Now, the de minimis tariff also stands at a whopping 90 percent, up from 30 percent a few days ago. (Trump said Wednesday, April 9, that he is raising tariffs on Chinese goods yet again, to 125 percent, while lowering tariffs on all other countries to 10 percent for 90 days.)\n\nIn addition, United States customs will also charge a tariff per â€œpostal item,â€ or shipment, as well. Between May 2 and June 1, the â€œincrease in per postal item containing goodsâ€ duty will be increased from $25 to $75. The order also includes a provision to boost this amount, after June 1, to $150.\n\nWhat this means for you: According to the amendment, the shop you buy from must report the value of the items, as well as the number of items, to U.S. Customs. Trumpâ€™s April 2 order was vague; it allows the U.S. government to apply a tariff of either 30 percent of the value of your order or else $25 per item. Now, Customs apparently can choose whether to tariff your shipment by 90 percent, or $75 per item. After June 1, the tariff rate (for now) is scheduled to remain the same, but U.S. Customs could increase the per-item tariff to a whopping $150 per item.\n\nSo how much will you be taxed to import cheap goods into the U.S. today, or after June 1? Itâ€™s not clear. Temu, for example, is headquartered in Boston, but is owned by a Chinese holding company; Shein is based in Singapore, but many of its operations are in China, too. AliExpress, owned by Chinese titan The Alibaba Group, is probably most clearly subject to Chinese tariffs. But storefronts like Amazon will also be subject to the tariffs, and anything shipped from China to the U.S. via Amazon will be tariffed, too.\n\nWhat is clear is that if youâ€™ve been used to buying cheap stuff â€” whether it be fast fashion or electronics â€” from Chinese shops or companies, those days appear to be over. Buckle up."}
{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-09T15:02:14Z", "url": "https://www.pcworld.com/article/2518204/windows-11-just-made-it-way-easier-to-type-emojis.html", "publishedAt": "2025-04-09T15:02:14Z", "content": "Skip to contentType your search and hit enter\r\nWhen you purchase through links in our articles, we may earn a small commission. This doesn't affect our editorial independence\r\n.\r\nUpdated April 9, 202â€¦ [+1809 chars]", "title": "Windows 11 just made it way easier to type emojis", "fullContent": "Updated April 9, 2025: Yesterday, with Aprilâ€™s Patch Tuesday update KB5055523, Microsoft rolled out the â€œemoji and moreâ€ panel thatâ€™s now accessible via a system tray icon in the taskbar. This feature was previously available in the optional KB5053656 update from March, and before that was available in the preview update mentioned below. The easiest way to install KB5055523 is via Windows Update.\n\nOriginal story from December 10, 2024: Microsoft seems to think Windows 11 users are clamoring for easier ways to insert emojis, as if weâ€™re so constantly in need of quick access to emojis on a day-to-day basis that we need super shortcuts for it.\n\nWell, if that describes you, Microsoft wants you to know that theyâ€™re listening and they care. In the latest Windows 11 Insiders preview (Build 22635.4580), Microsoft has added an emoji panel to the taskbar, granting immediate access to emojis no matter what youâ€™re doing.\n\nAlthough thereâ€™s already a keyboard shortcut for accessing the emoji panel â€” simply press Windows key + Period or Windows key + Semicolon â€” itâ€™s clear that not everyone is aware of it. After all, who can really remember the hundreds of keypress combinations that exist?\n\nIf you donâ€™t want the emoji panel in the taskbar, you can turn it off in the settings by navigating to Settings > Personalization > Taskbar, then under â€œSystem tray icons,â€ look for â€œEmojis and more.â€ Change the drop-down menu to Never to disable it.\n\nIf you arenâ€™t a Windows 11 Insider, this feature will come to you soon enough. Keep an eye out for update KB5046733 in Windows Update, but we have no word on when exactly it will arrive as of yet."}
{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-09T14:55:51Z", "url": "https://www.pcworld.com/article/2669591/this-whatsapp-security-flaw-leaves-your-pc-open-to-malware-update-now.html", "publishedAt": "2025-04-09T14:55:51Z", "content": "Skip to contentType your search and hit enter\r\nWhen you purchase through links in our articles, we may earn a small commission. This doesn't affect our editorial independence\r\n.\r\nDo you use WhatsApp?â€¦ [+1552 chars]", "title": "This WhatsApp security flaw leaves your PC open to malware. Update now!", "fullContent": "Do you use WhatsApp? If so, you need to be especially careful right now because thereâ€™s a security vulnerability in the Windows versionâ€”which many people still use every dayâ€”that can infect your PC with malware. WhatsApp has issued a security alert about the vulnerability, which is listed as CVE-2025-30401.\n\nBy exploiting this vulnerability, malicious actors can use attachments in MIME format (Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions)â€”a format the desktop version uses by defaultâ€”to inject malware on PCs. The theft of sensitive data is also possible with this method.\n\nThe risk of an attack that takes advantage of this flaw is relatively high, but an affected user must first interact with the MIME attachment for it to be actively exploited. Nevertheless, you should always be careful when receiving WhatsApp messages from people you donâ€™t know, especially when they contain unsolicited attachments.\n\nDangerous attachments are often disguised as harmless image filesâ€”and with one careless click, malware can be activated.\n\nIf you currently have WhatsApp for Windows installed on your PC, you should update to version 2.2450.6 (via the Microsoft Store) as soon as possible. In this version, the security vulnerability has been fixed and can no longer be actively exploited by attackers.\n\nThe normal WhatsApp app for Android and iOS devices is NOT affected by this issue, as the MIME format is only used for delivering content in the PC version of WhatsApp."}
