{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-09T14:20:40Z", "url": "https://www.pcworld.com/article/2669256/trump-threatens-additional-100-percent-tariffs-on-chip-giant-tsmc.html", "publishedAt": "2025-04-09T14:20:40Z", "content": "Skip to contentType your search and hit enter\r\nWhen you purchase through links in our articles, we may earn a small commission. This doesn't affect our editorial independence\r\n.\r\nAs the economy reelsâ€¦ [+3100 chars]", "title": "Trump threatens additional 100% tariffs on chip giant TSMC", "fullContent": "As the economy reels from President Trumpâ€™s punishing import taxes on Chinaâ€”now reaching a staggering 104 percentâ€”sectors of the tech industry are bracing for even more pain. Trump threatened TSMC, the worldâ€™s most prolific silicon chip manufacturer, with company-specific tariffs if they didnâ€™t accede to his demands.\n\nAccording to Reuters, Trump threatened Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company with an additional 100 percent tax â€œif you donâ€™t build your plant hereâ€ when speaking to the Republican National Congressional Committee. This would, presumably, be in addition to the current 32 percent tariff rate on imports from Taiwan itself. Approximately 60 percent of the worldâ€™s chip manufacturing occurs in Taiwan, focused on the most cutting-edge products, with TSMC producing the lionâ€™s share. The US currently manufactures 12 percent.\n\nTSMC, among competing chip manufacturers, had already committed to building fabrication plants within the United States as part of the CHIPS Act, a $52 billion stimulus package enacted during former President Bidenâ€™s administration. Last month, TSMC announced a $100 billion investment in US-based manufacturing centered in massive facilities in Arizona. This appears to be the announcement for which Trump is taking credit, in whole or in part.\n\nTSMCâ€™s current American capacity is completely sold through for the next two years. It seems extremely unlikely that TSMCâ€”or any chip manufacturerâ€”will be able to create enough output to supply even the domestic electronics demand of the United States within the next few years. The majority of new electronics will still need to be imported, in whole or in part, subjecting consumers to massively increased prices to offset the governmentâ€™s import taxes on goods and materials.\n\nCompanies like Razer have paused shipments of laptops entirely, and both Nintendo and Framework have delayed the pre-order process for the new Switch 2 gaming console and lower-priced Framework 12 laptop, respectively. Vaio is advertising â€œtariff-freeâ€ prices for its Japan-manufactured stock that presumably arrived in the US before tariffs began being levied against fresh supplies.\n\nWhile countries like South Korea and Japan are reportedly trying to negotiate with Trump, Chinaâ€™s position as the worldâ€™s leading manufacturer of finished goods puts it in a more advantageous position for trade negotiations, and it has instituted its own tariffs in response to Trumpâ€™s declarations. In short: China needs US imports far less than the US needs Chinese exports. Expect similar disruptions to continue indefinitely."}
{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-09T14:35:31Z", "url": "https://www.pcworld.com/article/2656156/framework-delays-laptop-12-pre-orders-in-the-u-s-due-to-tariffs.html", "publishedAt": "2025-04-09T14:35:31Z", "content": "Skip to contentType your search and hit enter\r\nWhen you purchase through links in our articles, we may earn a small commission. This doesn't affect our editorial independence\r\n.\r\nFramework announced â€¦ [+3587 chars]", "title": "Framework delays Laptop 12 pre-orders in the U.S. due to tariffs", "fullContent": "Framework announced a bunch of stuff last month: powerful AMD upgrades for its bread-and-butter Laptop 13 design, its first modular desktop, and a brand new, smaller, more affordable model, the Laptop 12. This 2-in-1 with a touchscreen is intended to offer repairability and upgrades to cheaper laptops. Now thereâ€™s a confirmed pre-order date, April 9.\n\nUpdate, Wednesday, April 9th: Framework has announced that it is delaying Framework 12 pre-orders for the United States, in response to president Trumpâ€™s tariffs, which are now as high as 104 percent on goods imported from China and 32 percent in Frameworkâ€™s primary supply partners in Taiwan. â€œWeâ€™re holding the next step, repricing products for sale in the US, until we have final confirmation that there is no alternative. Weâ€™ll keep you updated as we make changes, as well as on when weâ€™ll be able to open Framework Laptop 12 in the US.â€ Framework has also had to stop offering the least-expensive versions of the original 13-inch laptop design in the US, as import taxes would force it to be sold at a loss. Framework will open pre-orders to other countries it supplies later today. Update, Wednesday April 9thâ€¦again: The Trump admininstration has updated its tariff position, imposing an even steeper 125 percent tariff on Chinese import while lowering taxes to other countries, including Taiwan, down to 10 percent. Framework has re-implemented its existing prices for many existing laptops, with a 10 percent rise on some models, some storage, and pre-orders for the latest designs based around new AMD hardware. The Framework 12 has gone up for pre-order in Canada with a July delivery estimate, starding at $720 Canadian for a barebones model without OS, RAM, storage, or charger. But but the new design is still not available for pre-order in the United States. The original story from last week continues below.\n\nThe Framework 12 takes aim at budget designs that are â€ janky, locked-down, disposable, underpowered, and frankly, boring machines,â€ according to CEO Nirav Patel. And indeed, itâ€™s a colorful TPU/ABS plastic design offered in blue, pink, green, and a relatively buttoned-down silver or black, and thatâ€™s before you trick it out with the companyâ€™s signature add-on modules for various USB ports, HDMI ports, card readers, et cetera. Itâ€™s also the companyâ€™s first convertible design, with a 12-inch touchscreen thatâ€™s compatible with stylus input.\n\nThe Laptop 12 is intended to be a budget machine, or at least a budget alternative, so itâ€™s notably â€œchunkierâ€ than the existing Laptop 13 design. But it still has the same kind of hardware flexibility, with every internal and external component accessible to the user with a screwdriver, and four modular USB-C ports that can be swapped out on the fly. The Intel 13th-gen-based motherboard (i3 or i5) can handle up to 48GB of RAM and 2TB of M.2 storage, with a choice of Windows or Linux at purchase.\n\nWeâ€™re still waiting on perhaps the most crucial element of the Framework 12, the price. With the company specifically targeting low-price â€œcraptops,â€ the price of the design â€” particularly the cheapest configuration â€” will be a huge factor in whether it succeeds or not. After all, someone whoâ€™s budgeted for a $500 laptop has a lot harder time stretching up to the $1,000 mark, no matter how much more flexible and upgradeable the latter is. With import tariffs in the U.S. sending electronics prices ever higher, thereâ€™s still a lot of uncertainty floating around.\n\nWeâ€™ll find out in a week, I suppose. Thereâ€™s also no precise shipping date, though â€œmid-2025â€ was given at the announcement event. I hope Framework can hit approximately a $750 price tag with the Framework 12, otherwise itâ€™ll be a tough sell for the budget market."}
{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-09T14:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.pcworld.com/article/2659417/my-usb-cable-got-wet-can-i-still-use-it.html", "publishedAt": "2025-04-09T14:00:00Z", "content": "Skip to contentType your search and hit enter\r\nWhen you purchase through links in our articles, we may earn a small commission. This doesn't affect our editorial independence\r\n.\r\nA funny thing that hâ€¦ [+3028 chars]", "title": "My USB cable got wet. Can I still use it?", "fullContent": "A funny thing that happened to me recently was that I accidentally dunked the end of a USB cable in my coffee cup when I was moving it over my desk. â€œMy coffeeâ€™s going to give me a little extra energy boost today,â€ I thought as I pulled it out and examined the connector for drips of delicious, amber-colored goodness.\n\nBut as funny as it was, it raised an interesting question for me, that being: Could I simply use my USB cable right away as I had intended to do, or was my cable now roached? I wasnâ€™t sure, so I investigated. Hereâ€™s what I found outâ€¦\n\nWet USB cables: The lowdown\n\nWhile most USB cables are water resistant, itâ€™s important to note that this is the kind of water resistance you can expect from a knockoff 1980s analog wristwatch, meaning you can splash them a little bit without there being much of a problem, but you generally donâ€™t want to submerge them in water â€” theyâ€™re simply not made for that.\n\nThe most vulnerable part of a USB cable is the connector, since itâ€™s open to the environment and not bound by plastic or rubber. Regardless of where your cable gets wet, you should shut down the device youâ€™re using quickly and then unplug it if itâ€™s plugged in.\n\nYou also shouldnâ€™t use the cable right away but wait an hour or more until it dries out first. This ensures that youâ€™re not transferring the corrosive water (or coffee as it may be) to your USB port or allowing the liquid to damage the cable itself. You can also help dry out your cable with a few carefully applied techniques.\n\nHow to dry your cables\n\nIf your cable gets wet, you can use a cloth to dry it off, running a closed hand down its length. If the connector gets water inside it, give it a little shake to get any droplets out first. Then use the end of a tissue or a microfiber cloth to carefully poke inside and soak up any remaining droplets that remain there.\n\nI used the above techniques on my USB cable connector and found it worked perfectly once I plugged it in again.\n\nWant a quick solution? Try thisâ€¦\n\nA hairdryer can speed up the process of drying out a connector if it has water inside it, but there are a few steps youâ€™ll want to take to protect your cable from being melted by the hairdryerâ€™s powerful heat.\n\nFirst, you should always switch the hairdryer to the lowest heat setting.\n\nYouâ€™re also going to want to keep your cable at a safe distance from the hairdryerâ€™s nozzle, to ensure you get a constant flow of hot air that wonâ€™t start to burn the cable or connector â€” a distance of 14 inches should do the trick.\n\nA wet USB cable can be dried and used again. Pexels: Liza Summer\n\nDrying with a hairdryer should get your cable dry enough to reuse in just 15 minutes rather than several hours, but just be sure to check that itâ€™s completely dry before plugging it in.\n\nSo, in summary, while most cables do have some level of water resistance and will survive being splashed or momentarily dunked in water (or other beverage), you should still apply caution before using one again and dry it out completely to keep your devices safe from harm."}
