{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-09T14:23:22Z", "url": "https://finance.yahoo.com/news/evercore-starts-visa-mastercard-paypal-142322721.html", "publishedAt": "2025-04-09T14:23:22Z", "content": "Investing.com --Evercore ISI initiated coverage on Visa Inc (NYSE:V), Mastercard Inc (NYSE:MA), and PayPal Holdings Inc (NASDAQ:PYPL) with In Line ratings, viewing the payments leaders as defensive pâ€¦ [+2285 chars]", "title": "Evercore starts Visa, Mastercard, PayPal at In Line rating amid macro risks", "fullContent": "Investing.com --Evercore ISI initiated coverage on Visa Inc (NYSE:V), Mastercard Inc (NYSE:MA), and PayPal Holdings Inc (NASDAQ:PYPL) with In Line ratings, viewing the payments leaders as defensive plays in a volatile macro environment but noting valuation sensitivities and execution risks.\n\n\n\nEvercore sees Visa as a defensive stalwart, Mastercard is preferred on valuation while PayPalâ€™s turnaround depends on execution.\n\nVisaâ€™s long-term growth model remains intact, Evercore said, assigning a $330 price target, about 5% above its April 4 close.\n\n\n\nâ€œLike a fine wine, Visaâ€™s story gets better with age,â€ the analysts wrote, citing Visaâ€™s consistent formula of network expansion, product additions, and pricing leverage.\n\nVisaâ€™s stock has held up best among peers, there is still â€œdecent upsideâ€ from current levels and expects the shares to continue outperforming defensively if caution prevails in the broader market.\n\n\n\nKey growth drivers are Visaâ€™s value-added services (VAS) and commercial/B2B initiatives like Visa Direct.\n\nMastercard was also rated In Line, with a $550 price target implying 12% upside.\n\n\n\nEvercore said it prefers Mastercard over Visa near term, noting a narrower price-to-earnings spread and relative underperformance year-to-date.\n\nâ€œBoth the tortoise and the hare â€“ slow and steady plus opportunities for growth,â€ the analysts wrote, highlighting Mastercardâ€™s stronger VAS penetration and historically faster top-line growth despite its smaller scale.\n\nThe firm added that Mastercardâ€™s shares, while more volatile than Visaâ€™s, should remain a relative outperformer and could benefit more when markets turn, albeit likely lagging more deeply discounted fintech names in a rebound.\n\nPayPal also received an In Line rating, with a $65 target suggesting 11% upside.\n\n\n\nWhile Evercore acknowledged PayPalâ€™s large-scale consumer and merchant assets, it pointed to weak execution and macro sensitivity, particularly in its Branded Checkout segment.\n\nThe firm views PayPalâ€™s recent investor day as a step in the right direction, praising the strategyâ€™s clarity and the leadership team under CEO Alex Chriss. However, with macro conditions deteriorating, Evercore expects guidance to be revised down, in line with peers.\n\nRelated articles\n\nBenchmark initiates coverage of Integral Ad Science Holding LLC at 'hold'\n\nNewAmsterdam Pharma Announces Commencement of Secondary Offering of Ordinary Shares\n\nBitcoin Tops $27,000"}
